body:
I tried this code:

```rust
trait XYZ {
    type X: Copy;
}

#[derive(Clone, Copy)]
struct AAA<X: XYZ> {
    x: X::X,
}

struct B {}

impl XYZ for B {
    type X = usize;
}

impl Clone for B {
    fn clone(&self) -> Self {
        Self {}
    }
}

fn main() {
    let aaa: AAA<B> = AAA { x: 32 };

    let c1 = aaa;
    let c2 = aaa;
}
```

I expected to see this happen: 
AAA should implement a Copy, however it doesn't.

Instead, this happened: 
Instead it doesn't implement a copy and it shows an error:
```
   |
23 |     let aaa: AAA<B> = AAA { x: 32 };
   |         --- move occurs because `aaa` has type `AAA<B>`, which does not implement the `Copy` trait
24 | 
25 |     let c1 = aaa;
   |              --- value moved here
26 |     let c2 = aaa;
   |              ^^^ value used here after move```

If I add:
```
#[derive(Clone, Copy)]
struct B {}
```
everything is fine, so automatic deriver just sees whether all type parameters are Copy whereas it should check that all members of used in the type are copy.

